    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3594127970" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3594127970" />
    <a title="QNPoohBear" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22177907-qnpoohbear"><img alt="QNPoohBear" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1527904848p2/22177907.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3594127970?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="QNPoohBear" class="user" itemprop="url" name="QNPoohBear" href="/user/show/22177907-qnpoohbear">QNPoohBear</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/16176793-murder-must-advertise">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22177907-qnpoohbear?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3594127970" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11943455827147445168">When advertising agent Mr. Dean falls down a spiral staircase at work and breaks his neck, Pym&apos;s Publicity is left short-handed. Enter Death Bredon to fill the role. Some of the other agents sense something is off with this man- he dresses too nicely for a man making minimum wage but they figure he must either have been cut off from wealthy relatives or the difficult times have affected the formerly wealthy too. What they don&apos;t know is that Death is actually Lord Peter Wimsey, a private detectiv</span>
  <span id="freeText11943455827147445168" style="display:none">When advertising agent Mr. Dean falls down a spiral staircase at work and breaks his neck, Pym's Publicity is left short-handed. Enter Death Bredon to fill the role. Some of the other agents sense something is off with this man- he dresses too nicely for a man making minimum wage but they figure he must either have been cut off from wealthy relatives or the difficult times have affected the formerly wealthy too. What they don't know is that Death is actually Lord Peter Wimsey, a private detective hired by Mr. Pym to look into Mr. Dean's death to ensure no scandal is going to arise and ruin Pym's Publicity's good name. The more Death gets to know his co-workers and the rest of the staff, the more he becomes convinced Dean's fall was not an accident. He sets out to uncover the truth and the clues lead him straight to a den of iniquity where he must walk a tightrope between his dual identities and unravel the mysteries of the drug trade.<br /><br />Whew. This book is LONG and dense. I wanted to really like it but I struggled with it in the beginning. The beginning of the book sounds like a play written out in novel form. I can visualize people on a stage gathered around desks all talking rapid fire at once. It was hard to follow though without visual cues for the characters. The story gets lost in all the advertising jargon and detailed description of how the industry works. I don't think I fully understood or appreciated the humor. I couldn't keep track of all the characters. I just wanted to know who killed Dean and why! It picks up around the 20% mark when we finally meet Lord Peter as himself for the first time. There's a boring interlude about cricket before it comes to a thrilling conclusion. I stayed up late to finish because I couldn't put it down. I was rather disappointed the story revolved around Bright Young People and drugs. There were way too many unnecessary deaths and the conclusion wrapped up too neatly. The resolution for the murderer was depressing.<br /><br /> I can't really fault the author for dated language and expressions or the long discourse on where one went to school and how certain characters have a chip on their shoulder because they went to a state sponsored school and not a posh public school. Reading a book written in the 1930s is a lot different from reading a book SET in the 1930s so just be aware of that. <br /><br />Lord Peter seems like fun but rather silly. He thinks he's posing as his reprobate lookalike cousin <br />Death Bredon. That's "Deeth" to most people "afflicted" with the name but Lord Peter thinks there's something more "picturesque" to pronouncing it "deth". He likes to mess with people and act like a fool. The lookalike deception manages to fool everyone who isn't in on the secret, somehow it works, rather like Clark Kent and Superman. I think Lord Peter doesn't take the crime very seriously at first. He doesn't seem to take his job seriously either and acts like he's playing around when he's actually trying to gather clues. I think he was rather cruel to Dina and doesn't seem to take responsibility for causing several deaths. The only one he seems to really feel remorse for is the final one.<br /><br />Pamela Dean, sister of the late Mr. Dean, wants to know the truth about what happened to her brother. She's smart enough to be aware that he wasn't perfect or saintly. He was susceptible to a pretty face and charm, he loved money and enjoyed knowing secrets about people he could hold over them. I like her because she understands her brother's human frailties and just wants to see justice done. I was disappointed by the outcome of her story. Mr. Willis from Pym's is in love with her but he goes about expressing his interest in the wrong way. He hasn't learned Pamela doesn't like to be told what to do and no one wants to be preached at. Mr. Willis is an anxious, Puritanical sort of man who doesn't approve of much. He's dead set against Death Bredon. Could he be the murderer? <br /><br />Dian de Momerie is one of the Bright Young crowd. She's bored with life. She has too much money and not enough education or brains to do something worthwhile with her life so she's turned to alcohol and drugs. Under the influence she holds wild parties, participates in crazy stunts and meets one mysterious Harlequin she's drawn to in both good and bad ways. She holds the answer to part of the mystery but will she reveal it? Dian is a really awful person but I feel sorry for her that she doesn't have any purpose or meaning to her life and she throws it away. Her pal Tod Mulligan, on the other hand, is a terrible person. He purposefully deals drugs and enables Dian and others like her. He's cutthroat and is interested only in money. There is someone both Dian and Tod are afraid of but who is he?<br /><br />Pym's is full of eccentric characters. Mr. Pym is full of strong morals and always worried about scandal causing his downfall. Unfortunately the naughty joke was blanked out and from a distance of 90 years, it doesn't make sense. It was explained later and still from a distance of 90 years I didn't bat an eyelash. Poor Mr. Pym would be horrified to know what pops up in media today. Mrs. Crump, the charlady who brings afternoon tea, is a dear, sweet lady. She's in a position to know all and see all. Perhaps she knows more than she realizes? I felt super bad for her when she was accused of something she didn't do. She's one of my favorite people at Pym's. Her opposite, Miss Meteyard is cold and unfeeling. She seems well-educated and smart but just cold. I didn't like her at all. My other favorite employee is Joe "Ginger", an urchin who longs to be a detective. The kid has good instincts and knows how to get the information he needs. I think he will succeed at becoming a real detective, especially if Lord Peter helps. Mr. Tallboy, group manager for Nutrax is overworked and stressed. He takes it out on everyone else and is very fussy about their fussiest client. Mr. Ingleby is asked to show Bredon around and they seem like they share a similar sense of the absurd. There's something not quite right about it. The most detestable employee is Mr. Copley, a cranky old, old-fashioned man who complains about everything. He thinks he knows better than everyone else and his health problems make him extra mean. Most of the other employees are not very memorable. <br /><br />Peter's brother-in-law, Chief Inspector Parker, seems to take Peter's antics in stride and doesn't mind assistance from Peter. Peter seems like a good, family man, settled into middle-aged domesticity and not the sort to go running after criminals but he does a good job on his end to wrap up the case.<br /><br />I read this book because I was curious about it after reading <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/50482959.Murder_Is_a_Must" title="Murder Is a Must by Marty Wingate" rel="nofollow noopener">Murder Is a Must</a> and the search for the lost rare signed first edition of this book. I'm glad I read it but I'll stick with my light and fluffy cozy mysteries.<br /><br />Don't read this book if you're tired or looking for something to read before bed. Read this on a rainy day with a cup of tea or several. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11943455827147445168" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


